The '''American Osteopathic Board of Proctology (AOBPR)''' is an organization that provides [[board certification]] to qualified [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of disorders of the [[anus]], [[colon (anatomy)|colon]], and [[rectum]] of the [[gastrointestinal tract]] ([[Colorectal surgery|proctologists]]). The board is one of 18 [[Specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] certifying boards of the [[American Osteopathic Association Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists]] approved by the [[American Osteopathic Association]] (AOA),<ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Specialty Certifying Boards|url=https://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/aoa-specialty-boards.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> and was established in 1941.<ref name=OstBoardCert09>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=Ronald E.|coauthors=Scheinthal, S; Gross, C; Bell, EC|title=Osteopathic specialty board certification.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2009|month=March|volume=109|issue=3|pages=181–90|pmid=19336771|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/109/3/181.long|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> As of April 2011, there were 25 osteopathic proctologists certified by the AOBPR.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=RE|coauthors=Scheinthal, S; Gross, C; Bell, EC|title=Osteopathic specialty board certification.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2011|month=April|volume=111|issue=4|pages=280–8|pmid=21562298|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/111/4/280.full|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> 
 
==Board certification==
To become board certified in proctology, candidates must have completed an AOA-approved [[medical residency|residency]] in proctology and one year of practice as a licensed proctologist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residencies (Training and Certification)|url=http://aocpr.com/residencies.htm|publisher=American Osteopathic College of Proctology|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>  Additionally, candidates must have successfully completed the required oral and written examinations. Since 2004, board certified osteopathic proctologists must renew their certification every ten years to avoid expiration of their board certified status.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ramirez|first=AF|coauthors=Bell, EC|title=Osteopathic specialty board certification.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2007|month=March|volume=107|issue=3|pages=117–25|pmid=17485568|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/107/3/117.full|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castleconnolly.com/resources/osteopathic.cfm|title=Medical Boards: Osteopathic |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=Castle Connolly Medical Ltd. |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> Physicians certified by the AOBPR are known as fellows of the American Osteopathic College of Proctology.

